column11: The question will resolve based on the closing price reported at CNBC using the 1Y graph. The closing price can be found by hovering your cursor over the relevant date. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

With a daily vol of 5.1% and annualized vol of 80% of price change on bitcoin I see it as a high probability it will close above $10K with only three trading days left. I don't have any hunch of geo political insight to add to the analysis but strictly used historical vol to estimate probabilities.

I'm thinking about this more and I feel like $10k might carry some bizarre psychological weight. People will think "deal!" if they see it below $10k and jump in, pushing the price back up over the short-term. It doesn't matter that not too long ago the price was below $10k, just that there is a line of people with a case of FOMO.

Bitcoin has been extremely volatile lately. Over the past three months bitcoin has traded at a low $5,600 to a high of $19,500. With no true basis of economic return to assess (i.e. cash flows), it is fairly impossible to predict its price. It's price is based on supply and demand, which is largely speculative at this point. I am adjusting my forecast lower than I previously thought. The price can conceivably be at any level. There is no reason to say it can't be at $4,000 or $500,000. I am adjusting it to 50/50 of between $7000-10,000 and "more than $10,000".

Few reasons I'm increasing the likelihoods of the lower brackets: 1. Obviously today's BTC/USD price drop has been spectacular. Similar to what we saw from 18-22 December last year. Possible that this is the first day of the "fire sale" and similarly to mid-December more such down days are to follow. 2. BTC regulation related woes are continuing. France and Germany are now calling for BTC regulation, ROK is still working on how to ban crypto currency markets and China's central bank looks to tighten ban on crypto currency trade. https://euobserver.com/tickers/140555 https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-markets-bitcoin/bitcoin-other-cryptocurrencies-tumble-on-government-crackdown-worries-idUSKBN1F50UV https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-bitcoin/pboc-official-says-chinas-centralized-virtual-currency-trade-needs-to-end-source-idUSKBN1F50FZ 3. I concur with @Censusguyz point that first BTC futures positions are maturing (17th of January the deadline for the first contracts) and thus at least "hedgers" on both losing and winning side of these positions are trying to cut their losses. Hence the sell side of trading could in my view see another uptick in the next few days. https://www.ethnews.com/market-manipulation-101-bitcoin-futures

Crypto will have a place in society going forward. Many people think it will be the next beanie baby, and many others think it will keep going up. The truth is far less dramatic. Value in Bitcoin will fade all year, one of the most prominent reason, is the proliferation of so many cryptocurrencies. Bitcoin also has structural problems and it is very hard to use in real life. That will be resolved in the long term, but building out the infrastructure will take time. Bitcoin with have a long downtrend over 18.

Twelve days to go and the overall trend is downward. Churn still is spectacularly high. For example, from 8AM to 9AM MST today, ~ 3 million Bitcoins changed hands amid a drop in price bottoming out at ~$12,870. Those three million Bitcoins represent ~ one fifth of all Bitcoins in existence. I still cannot imagine how the price isn't more volatile, given the lack of underlying value and the churn rate. The only reason I am giving such a high probability to >$10K is that the behavior of the overall system bespeaks some sort of collusion to keep the little guys in the game -- AKA marks, AKA suckers, the guys who read make money fast in Bitcoin ads in the airline magazines.

Entering dead man's curve. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_Man%27s_Curve Agreeing with @Anneinak on the institutional folks. The bad guys are in litecoin more now due to transaction overhead. https://ounce.me/ http://fiatleak.com/
With just 2 weeks left, highly unlikely to break below 7K mark. Adjusting accordingly.

Raising probability of >$10K on the basis of reduced volatility. Despite staggeringly high churn and no obvious floor to Bitcoin, despite the overall falling trend during the last week, there always has been plenty of buyers stepping up whenever the price falls.

Driven by demand supply via investor psychology and regulatory action. Regulatory intervention could trigger catastrophic decline hence 5% to 0-1000. Price behavior shows (rough calculations) drawdowns of approximately 30% depth occurring 7 times in the past 2yrs. Given the current price & time remaining for the forecast this level of draw down would trigger <$10k but would remain unlikely. Clearly the lack of fundamentals tempt me to increase the probability of catastrophic price falls based on what I think should happen. Markets can remain irrational longer than you can stay solvent...
Crypto is hot and Bitcoin has the premiere 'brand' right now.
The price is staying pretty stable above $10,000. See my earlier forecasts for more discussion.

Moving up probability of >$10K on the basis that every time the price falls significantly, there seems to be a bottomless pit of people ready to buy and thus pull the price back up. What really astonishes me is how short a time it takes watching the tickers on bitfinex and coinbase to see trades of over $1B each, and the market hardly bobbles in response. It's a fascinating opportunity, albeit through a glass darkly, to observe the international money laundering trade. http://bitcoinity.org/markets

This is the latest shining example of the Greater Fool theory of investing. One question concerns the timing of the bubble burst. The next Bitcoin heist would certainly cause a panic and plummet prices, but now some major institutions have a vested interest in silencing news of any such heist. Also, the current price spike is fueled by the "novelty" (many having just heard of Bitcoin), which should subside over the coming weeks.

Just now, a transaction on Coinbase worth $2,303,252,000 USD at $15,050 USD per coin. That's 153,040 Bitcoins out of the ~16M in circulation, or ~ 1% in just one transaction . This transaction correlated with an almost immediate rise of $90 USD in the price of Bitcoins.
This is my first forecast and I am familiar with the subject

Beware the bears! The little guys (many of whom read those airline magazine ads for Bitcoin sales) are piling in expecting it to rise, while the big guys are shorting it. Whales might be the exception to the big guys because I don't know who they are. The little guys who bought early and are simply holding their coins (hodlers) are also betting Bitcoin will rise, but unlike the newbie small investors, they have an almost religious belief that in the long run, Bitcoin always will go up.
19 days to go. In weeks it has stabilized around 15000 (+/- 2000) :). Time to bring my prediction to match that of the consensus :).
The exuberance seems strong enough to carry on as long as overall economic conditions provide people with disposable wealth.

BTC appears to remain resilient to news on other cryptocurrencies, the Israeli regulators' trade ban movement, South Korea's bans and other developments. Also CBOE futures trading appears to have slightly brought down volatility. While any development may well lead to violent moves in the price, there is little to indicate a forthcoming collapse (today's price = $16336)
Showing resilience in the face of plenty of bad news and publicity over the last week or so.
Being part of the crowd, I see that there's still not much money coming in. It's world-wide phenomenon after all.

2 reasons; one is the emerging equity markets leaning into btc will doubtless bolster the price, and reason two is that it's too soon for China to intentionally deflate prices to successfully eviscerate American middle class wealth. They will wait until we are properly gut-hooked on digital Beanie Babies before they play the liquidity shock card, and will be the first to find seats once the music stops. Remember that maybe >2% of BTC will get cashed out at market value before the remaining holders race to undercut each other, clogging exchanges with unfilled (and unfillable) sell orders, sending prices spiraling to pennies per.

$16.89K right now, and I just saw the market absorb a $1/2B trade without a blink. Trading volume around 5M bitcoins/hr out of the ~16M in circulation. This high volume suggests instability, yet new suckers are likely joining the game via those airline magazine ads. Raising probability of >$10K slightly.

Airline magazines now are brimming with ads for Bitcoin sales. Get rich fast! Between that and Peter Thiel's bet (https://www.wsj.com/articles/peter-thiels-founders-fund-makes-big-bet-on-bitcoin-1514917433), it looks like there are enough get rich fast types to hold the price above $10K at least until after Jan. 26.
Seems like for now there is enough demand to keep the price above $10,000. (The categories may have made sense when the question was posted, but not now :)).

Significant volatility lately may lead to relative stability as the major holders do not want to see their investments totally eliminated so fast. Also tons of hype and people may see current levels as an opportunity.

Bitcoin prices seem to have "stabilized" (said with tongue firmly in cheek) between $12,000 and $18,000 over the pst two weeks. With news yesterday of Peter Thiel's moonshot bet on Bitcoin, I believe the price will only rise in the near term.

I'm moving up the probability of over $10 K on the basis of trading patterns over the last week. I look at the correlation between spikes in trading volume and sudden changes in price. Volume spikes correlate with fast changes both up or down. Also I have been watching the ratio of small vs gigantic single exchange events. When Bitcoin was almost falling to $10K, there were many huge trades. But in recent days the trades have been more modest in size overall, even when the volume was in the range of 25% of all circulating Bitcoins within an hour.
Many investors sold their bitcoins over christmas and new year cause of risk management. Beginning of January 2018 people reinvest their money in bitcoins.
Only a few weeks remaining, but crash to below 10,000$ is still plausible.

Because either bitcoin stabilizes at current level above 10k (50%) or market diversifies further (30%) for reasons of market acceptance of e funds trading, or, market breaks up further with more e monetary opps in 3rd world economies (10%) leaving bitcoin in the 4-7K range, or bit exchanges fail because of dark web intrusions by gov. agencies and prosecution of criminal and perceived criminal activity leaving bitcoin at 1-4k for stalwart investors

The commodity traders have shorted everything as people hedge there coins, Commodity trading is sucking the value out of the Coins. Tradings stops are in on most exchanges or this would have continued today.

Whale spotting. Just a few minutes ago, a ~$3.6B USD transaction on Bitfinex. It seems that a major correction if not a burst of the bubble is in motion. Looking at the CNBC price tracker the price fell $100 dollars in minute and half around 14:50 CET. The volatility is in the excess of 20%. Seems impossible to predict where the price will stabilized, however I assume it will be below $10 000. Hence I'm increasing the likelihood that BTC will finish under 10 000 by the closing date. Crazy day :).

Twitter has lots of anecdotal data on the tsunami of marks rushing to be fleeced by the Bitcoin whales. Looks like there are enough marks to carry the fleecing through 26 Jan. Example anecdote, from an economics Nobelist (who predicted the Great Recession of 2008):

I'm trying to get a handle on the bitcoin "whales," gigantic traders who shift in and out by the billions USD. In the last 24 hours, ~$17B was traded. Considering that the market cap right now is ~$260B. It doesn't take watching for long to see individual trades of a significant fraction of a $B, for example the half billion USD trade I saw on Bitfinex this morning. That's 1/6 of a percent of the market cap in one swell foop! That's why I ascribe much of the current trading volume to whales.
$15,030 right now at Bitfinex http://bitcoinity.org/markets. I just watched a transaction worth half a billion fly by on its ticker. The whales are active. The marks are getting taken. Oh, what fun!

While I'm rising my percentage point of BTC closing near $10 000 the decline of the last few days still makes me a cautious. Hence I still see there a higher possibility than the crowd of BTC falling into one of the lower brackets.

However, given the world wide attention the currency has garnered, plus the inclusion of futures contracts for the currency, I believe the speculation has room to run between now (12/19/2017) and Jan 26, 2018. I am stating that the price of bitcoin can stay above $10,000 over the next 38 days.

As more and more regulatory and conventional exchanges acknowledge bitcoin, the price will continue to increase. Still, there exists the chance as commodity traders become part of the bitcoin market the price may be driven by the vagaries of institutional trading.

I do not consider these to be zero probability ranges however, as reviewing the historic prices of BTC, there have been drops of 93% and 85% at different points, and in a period of days it has dropped 50% - 66% prior to a persistent decline. I based my forecast on the fact that the btc is around 6k usd right now. I looked at the risk, the past prices and guessed the following.

The starting point for the forecast is looking at how much Bitcoin's price had grown (or contracted) 3 months after a point in time. I looked at a year of daily closing prices starting on 29 July 2016. This gave a possible increase in price by 26 January 2018 ranging from c.5% to c.197% on the basis of historic performance alone and formed the baseline for the forecast. The baseline was then modified to reflect a range of analyst opinions backing outcomes from Bitcoin collapse to a surge in growth.
